    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>Mary Raymond Shipman Andrews (1860-1936) was an American author, dramatist, novelist, poet, 
and short story writer.  Her best known piece is <emph render="italic">The Perfect Tribute</emph>, 
a short story about Abraham Lincoln.  Her husband was a judge of the New York Court of Appeals; 
they resided in Taunton, New York.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The <emph render="bold">Mary Raymond Shipman Andrews Papers</emph> is divided into two series.  
<emph render="bold">Writings</emph> consists of handwritten notes and drafts, typescripts, a few 
clippings of printed short stories, and one book.  
<emph render="bold">Miscellaneous</emph> contains limited correspondence, some family letters 
dating from 1808, some family writings, news clippings and memorabilia.</p>
<p>Of special interest are letters written by Thomas Gold, Mr. Andrews' grandfather, to Peter 
Smith, abolitionist, and several letters to Judge and Mrs. Andrews from Theodore Roosevelt.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
      <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
      <p>Writings are subdivided by type.  Miscellaneous is arranged alphabetically by type of material.</p>
    </arrangement>
